Meningiomas are typically benign tumors that originate from the meninges of the brain. They are characterized histologically by a syncytial growth pattern of cells with round to oval nuclei, often with a clear or slightly eosinophilic cytoplasm. The presence of intravascular growth and invasion, as well as the formation of psammoma bodies (concentrically laminated calcifications), are also common features of meningiomas.However, it is important to note that a definitive diagnosis would require further histological examination and possibly immunohistochemical staining. The absence of high-grade features such as necrosis, increased mitotic activity, or prominent nucleoli in the current field of view does not rule out the possibility of a higher-grade meningioma elsewhere in the tumor.
